WEBVTT

00:02.680 --> 00:07.707
Bill Tift at the University of California, 
University of Arizona. Well, he's from the

00:07.727 --> 00:14.237
University of Arizona, but we're currently at the 
Student Union of the University of California.

00:14.317 --> 00:20.025
Okay, so let's get started at the beginning, and 
Bill, for the record, give your full name. William

00:20.045 --> 00:21.147
Grant Tift. And where and when were you born? April 
5th, 1932 in Derby, Connecticut. How did you first

00:28.838 --> 00:31.101
get interested in astronomy? This has to do with 
the history of planetary astronomy. I never

00:36.538 --> 00:37.920
wanted to be anything else. I became interested in 
science or knew I was going to be a scientist about

00:39.481 --> 00:48.529
fourth grade in school in astronomy by the time I 
was in eighth grade. And through a local amateur

00:48.549 --> 01:01.020
astronomer, elderly lady in my hometown, I met 
Dirk Brouwer at Yale.

01:02.570 --> 01:31.480
the next major step well in various amateur 
activities AAVSO things like that Westinghouse

01:02.570 --> 01:31.480
Science Talent Search I was one of the trip winners 
in 1950 to Washington and got to know Harlow

01:02.570 --> 01:31.480
Shapley Harvard was the obvious place to go to get 
undergraduate training and so I went to Harvard as

01:02.570 --> 01:31.480
an undergraduate and you were an astronomy major I 
was an astronomy major which is kind of rare well

01:02.570 --> 01:31.480
there were a number of us several other names that 
are Well, one in planetary astronomy is one of my

01:31.747 --> 01:40.395
roommates was Fred Franklin at CFA. He's, I 
believe, in planetary astronomy. Yes, and I

01:44.038 --> 01:46.980
interviewed him in England. We were roommates at 
Harvard. And Dick Sears, who's known in

01:50.824 --> 01:56.208
astronomy, was one of the... So we had astronomy 
majors in those days. When did you get your

01:58.390 --> 02:00.252
bachelor's degree? 1954. Okay, and then where'd 
you go to grad school? Caltech. Why did you pick

02:04.859 --> 02:05.780
Caltech? Because astronomy was disintegrating 
at Harvard. That was when Bach left Harvard and it

02:09.143 --> 02:18.311
switched from an observational institution in 
the Shapley Revolution. When Shapley resigned

02:19.272 --> 02:29.682
and the Southern Hemisphere Observatory was 
potentially being closed and things like that, it

02:19.272 --> 02:29.682
was not a time to go on in observational astronomy 
and Caltech was the obvious place where

02:30.168 --> 02:36.516
first-rate observational astronomy was being 
done. So I went to Caltech. And

02:40.020 --> 02:46.348
what was your thesis and who was your thesis 
advisor for your PhD? OK. My thesis was on the

02:46.969 --> 02:58.403
photometry of the nuclei, nuclear regions of 
galaxies, well, photometry of galaxies on an

02:46.969 --> 02:58.403
eight-color system. My advisor was Art Code.

03:03.972 --> 03:15.248
He was at Caltech at that time and then

03:03.972 --> 03:15.248
later left Caltech. I guess he went back to 
Wisconsin as director at that time. Bill Baum was

03:20.134 --> 03:24.340
my other sort of advisor. I say sort of advisor 
because I actually saw art code only twice during

03:24.843 --> 03:31.690
my thesis, the beginning and at one intermediate 
point. I had one discussion with Bill Baum.

03:34.272 --> 03:35.894
Otherwise, I pretty much did it myself. When did 
you get your PhD? 1958. Okay, and what did you do

03:40.758 --> 03:42.500
then? I went as a postdoc to Australia to work on 
Magellanic Cloud problems. With Bach? Well, Bach

03:50.864 --> 03:55.270
was director then, and it was through Bach that I 
made the arrangements. But again, it was a program

03:55.751 --> 03:58.454
I designed myself. I wasn't working specifically 
with anyone. Okay, now, so when did you leave

04:01.638 --> 04:04.102
Australia? Okay, Australia, I was a two-year 
National Science Foundation postdoc. I left

04:11.992 --> 04:19.943
there in 1959

04:11.992 --> 04:19.943
and finished the last few months of the postdoc 
at... Caltech, and then I had arranged a job in

04:20.294 --> 04:39.665
Nashville

04:20.294 --> 04:39.665
with Carl Seifert at the University of, well, at 
Vanderbilt University, Dyer Observatory.

04:41.187 --> 04:45.995
Unfortunately, Carl Seifert had been killed in an 
automobile accident. As a matter of fact, it was It

04:47.918 --> 04:52.363
happened an hour before I arrived in Nashville for 
my first visit. I was met by a graduate student, in

04:53.565 --> 05:02.976
fact, Charles Tolbert, well-known in astronomy, 
who told me that Carol had just been killed in an

04:53.565 --> 05:02.976
automobile accident. I went to Seaford's 
funeral.

05:08.822 --> 05:14.449
But that changed what was to be a three-year 
appointment working in high-latitude blue stars

05:15.307 --> 05:31.102
to a one-year appointment, immediately looking 
for a job, which is when, well, I had previously met

05:15.307 --> 05:31.102
John Hall and was interested in possibilities at 
Lowell, and so I immediately picked up that

05:15.307 --> 05:31.102
thread. And since Harold Johnson had just left 
Lowell and they had just acquired the Ohio State

05:32.543 --> 05:41.972
69-inch telescope, And I had the kind of 
credentials both in photometry and experience

05:42.357 --> 05:48.688
with large telescopes. So basically I was offered 
Errol Johnson's job at Lowell. So I was actually at

05:54.037 --> 05:56.381
Vanderbilt then only for one year. Okay, when you 
got to Lowell, what was the place like?

06:04.936 --> 06:11.624
Well, it's a beautiful place to live and a 
beautiful place to enjoy yourself. Perhaps one of

06:12.065 --> 06:17.552
the most wonderful settings and pleasant places 
to live. But I think the one thing which is most

06:18.433 --> 06:27.965
obvious about Lowell, was obvious then, was the 
extremely tight budget under which they

06:18.433 --> 06:27.965
operated. The question of the controls of the 
Lowell estate and a fairly small section, a

06:32.729 --> 06:39.501
portion of which was devoted to maintaining the 
observatory. And although I don't know many of the

06:40.924 --> 06:56.391
details, I know there was a lot of concern about 
whether any of the additional estate money would

06:40.924 --> 06:56.391
become available to astronomy.

06:57.265 --> 07:12.085
I never really went into any discussions on this, 
but there was a lot of concern as to how you could

06:57.265 --> 07:12.085
operate an effective modern observatory on the 
extremely small amounts of money which were

06:57.265 --> 07:12.085
available. You mentioned yesterday that early on 
in the space program, when it was about time you

07:14.287 --> 07:26.884
were getting involved, the powers that be or 
whoever decided that they really didn't want to

07:14.287 --> 07:26.884
get involved with the space program because it 
didn't have the base on which to do it, which is kind

07:27.067 --> 07:32.575
of surprising in that later that they did get the 
Planetary Data Center and everything. Could you

07:32.595 --> 07:33.917
say that for the record? Well,

07:33.937 --> 07:44.152
for various reasons, part of them personal in my 
own life, I was going through approaching divorce

07:33.937 --> 07:44.152
and so on. It was a certain feeling on my part that I 
needed some change. The space program was

07:48.578 --> 07:53.445
developing, and I wrote a letter at one point to the 
Institute for of Astrophysics, or whatever it is,

07:53.662 --> 08:18.454
the NASA Institute in New York City, I believe, and 
expressing interest in space astronomy, and was

07:53.662 --> 08:18.454
referred to Jocelyn Gill and, I forget his first 
name, Foster's division in NASA on manned space

07:53.662 --> 08:18.454
astronomy, and They invited me back to Washington 
for a while. I went back as a consultant for a couple

08:21.430 --> 08:23.513
of months. What year was this, roughly? It had been 
around 19... Well, I went to Lowell in 61. Probably

08:29.081 --> 08:34.468
the original correspondence here was in 62, 
possibly as late as 63. When I came back from

08:35.630 --> 08:44.281
Washington, I was quite interested in the space 
program and potentially interested in applying

08:35.630 --> 08:44.281
to the astronaut program. In fact, I did apply 
later in 1965. But... I remember having

08:49.636 --> 09:09.425
discussions with John Hall and expressing my 
interest in the space program and getting this

08:49.636 --> 09:09.425
feedback or concern that, well, this really was 
not the kind of direction that they felt that they

08:49.636 --> 09:09.425
could support the program. That if I was 
interested in going into this, that perhaps this

09:09.465 --> 09:15.795
wasn't the proper base to operate from. And of 
course, they had hired me. in a completely

09:18.610 --> 09:32.827
different context, basically, to use, I mean, to 
do photometry with some of the large, their newer

09:18.610 --> 09:32.827
large telescope, well, the 6090s. Not that it was 
that great a telescope, because it wasn't at that

09:32.867 --> 09:39.716
time, until they redid it a few years later. And 
made it into a, what, a 72-inch? 72-inch, with a

09:41.618 --> 09:43.600
quality mirror. I spent a lot of time Well, there 
were two problems. One, the 69-inch was not a

09:46.934 --> 09:49.357
high-quality telescope. You couldn't do imagery 
with it. The images tended to distort rapidly as a

09:55.445 --> 09:59.891
function of temperature changes. I remember 
doing a lot of installation work on the telescope,

10:00.792 --> 10:05.539
trying to control the figure on the mirror. And 
also, because of the very low budgets at Lolo, they

10:06.320 --> 10:12.127
had very little instrumentation. There was no 
equipment, really, to go with it. One reason they

10:14.534 --> 10:19.578
had hired me was I did have my own part of my own 
photometer. Harold Johnson had taken all the

10:20.079 --> 10:29.767
equipment with him when he left, and there really 
was no working equipment. I got a small O&R grant

10:29.787 --> 10:42.098
with which I built up a working photometer and did 
use the 69-inch to extend the work that I had done as

10:29.787 --> 10:42.098
my dissertation. That was my main new scientific 
research that I did at Lowell. But in parallel, I

10:48.028 --> 10:51.972
was developing this interest in the space 
program. And it was that aspect that,

10:51.992 --> 11:09.450
well, John Lowell specifically was a little 
apprehensive about whether this was an

10:51.992 --> 11:09.450
appropriate type of development that Lowell 
wanted to support. Let me just get something in for

11:10.171 --> 11:11.793
the record. When did you leave Lowell? 1964, 
essentially. Initially, it was halftime, I

11:17.714 --> 11:23.282
think, from July to October of 64. I was halftime at 
Lowell and halftime at Arizona. And then in

11:27.508 --> 11:31.053
October of 64, I was full-time at Arizona. Where 
you have been since then. Where I've been there

11:32.695 --> 11:34.257
since then, that's correct. I went there as 
associate professor and was promoted to full

11:34.277 --> 11:41.427
professor in 1973.

11:41.947 --> 11:43.970
when you were at Lowell. Now, Lowell's, of course, 
famous to the public for its planetary and

11:45.252 --> 11:59.493
particularly Mars studies, but of course they 
always did, right from the very beginning, a lot of

11:45.252 --> 11:59.493
stellar and galactic work, for which, of course, 
they didn't get the credit that they deserved. But

12:00.595 --> 12:10.249
when you were there, what was the attitude towards 
planetary versus stellar and galactic and

12:00.595 --> 12:10.249
extragalactic work? Well, there was a strong 
support, I think, or a feeling that the work that

12:10.448 --> 12:28.553
Harold had done and the study of star clusters, 
there wasn't much experience there in galaxies,

12:10.448 --> 12:28.553
although I remember having discussions with some 
of the U.S. Naval Observatory people. There had

12:29.874 --> 12:37.705
been some interesting work that had been done by,

12:29.874 --> 12:37.705
hmm, what was his name? some multicolor 
photography or multicolor imagery that had been

12:38.495 --> 12:44.862
done on galaxies at Naval Observatory. I think 
they were quite enthusiastic, actually, about

12:46.284 --> 12:51.670
the work that I was doing on galaxy photometry. It 
fit rather nicely into the kind of things that

12:51.730 --> 12:58.537
Harold had been initially exploring. I'd also 
done work in star clusters and things, so I had a lot

12:59.038 --> 13:06.426
in common in principle with the kinds of things 
that Harold Johnson had been doing. And I think

13:06.760 --> 13:09.403
they were very enthusiastic about that kind of 
work. I encountered

13:10.224 --> 13:27.585
very little feeling that Lowell had a planetary 
orientation, or there certainly was no pressure

13:10.224 --> 13:27.585
in any sense to be doing anything that was 
connected with planetary work. I think they

13:27.625 --> 13:36.396
considered their work potentially quite 
broad-based.

13:37.456 --> 13:55.659
One of the very visible programs there was Henry 
Giklis' work on proper motions of red faint stars,

13:37.456 --> 13:55.659
and I actually was considering some observations 
of some of the proper motion stars. I'd say it was a

13:56.300 --> 14:03.008
fairly broad-based program, stellar, 
extragalactic, and obviously planetary, but

13:56.300 --> 14:03.008
that wasn't an aspect that I had much connection. 
Did you ever feel that you were considered by real

14:03.038 --> 14:10.650
astronomers to be second rate because you were at 
Lowell instead of, say, Mount Holson? No, I didn't

14:10.670 --> 14:12.273
have that feeling at all. I thought Lowell was a 
highly respected observatory. It was recognized

14:15.758 --> 14:19.464
that they had budgetary or monetary problems. 
But, for example, my request for an O&R grant was

14:21.928 --> 14:28.438
very well received. And Lowell, I think, was a very 
respected observatory. And the people that were

14:32.281 --> 14:37.748
there, not that there weren't very many of us, but 
Bill Sinton was well-known. And, of course,

14:38.208 --> 14:43.535
Harold Johnson had been extremely well-known. It 
was a small group, but I think my general

14:44.076 --> 14:50.503
impression was highly regarded. Now, you overlap 
with some of the real old-timers there, and that's

14:51.925 --> 14:57.913
what I want to hit you for. Yeah, yeah. Of

14:58.642 --> 15:13.358
the Slipher brothers, I knew EC moderately. That 
is, I met him a couple of times, had a few

15:13.438 --> 15:16.742
discussions with him. Vesto, I saw a few times. He 
was not around the observatory very much. And that

15:26.485 --> 15:31.312
was really before I got into my modern work in 
galaxies. In a way, I wish I'd had a chance to have

15:31.332 --> 15:38.363
actually talked to some of them about some of the 
early redshift work that they did. I never

15:38.443 --> 15:40.666
actually had any direct contact on that. For the 
record, of the two brothers, E.C. was the one who

15:44.472 --> 15:45.634
did what? The two Slipher brothers. Well, again, 
you probably know. I mean, I don't know the

15:52.063 --> 15:53.526
history. Which one was the Mars guy? Well, I assume 
EC was more of the planetary oriented, and Vesto a

15:55.696 --> 16:02.530
little more. Well, I know Vesto, I believe, was the 
one who did the

16:03.371 --> 16:11.207
actual ridge observations. interesting in that 
if you go back into elementary textbooks of 10 or 20

16:11.542 --> 16:22.257
years ago, it's always Hubble, Hubble, Hubble, 
and now people have been getting their act

16:11.542 --> 16:22.257
together, and they note that it was really Slipher 
that did it. Slipher did the actual first

16:22.277 --> 16:24.239
observations. That's correct. Slipher was the 
one who made the observations, though I believe

16:25.201 --> 16:32.451
it's fair to say it was Hubble that recognized the 
significance. And I don't really know what the

16:32.471 --> 16:35.695
communication chains were between... I mean, 
they obviously knew each other, and I think it...

16:42.372 --> 16:51.100
Any material or information that was collected by 
Schleifer became known and was used, at least as a

16:42.372 --> 16:51.100
starting point, for Hubble. What exactly how it 
influenced Hubble's beginning, I have really no

16:51.140 --> 16:55.083
idea. But it puzzles me in a way, and that's why I 
wish I had known at the time what I was going to be

16:56.204 --> 17:12.058
doing later, because it would have been very 
interesting to talk to the Schleifer brothers

16:56.204 --> 17:12.058
about what were their original motivations for 
doing this, and what were their impressions.

17:12.410 --> 17:14.453
Unfortunately, I have no idea. They obviously 
didn't pursue it or follow it up the way Hubble did.

17:21.982 --> 17:29.432
So whether they considered it just a curiosity or 
whether they really thought deeply about what

17:21.982 --> 17:29.432
this might mean, I don't know. But they preceded 
the knowledge of what they were looking at. And I

17:34.558 --> 17:42.028
believe part of the original motivation for their 
observations were undoubtedly the idea that

17:34.558 --> 17:42.028
perhaps galaxies were We've seen this in the 
literature, but again, I don't have it as a direct

17:42.683 --> 17:46.767
statement for this life. Galaxies were 
considered as possible solar systems in

17:47.587 --> 17:53.773
formation. That was one of the old concepts. Did 
you ever meet Lamplin? No. Because there was a lot

18:00.319 --> 18:05.023
of radiometry that went on in the 20s and 30s. I knew 
Edison Pettit, but that was back through... In

18:08.106 --> 18:12.150
fact, Edison Pettit was the man who built the 
photometer that I took to Australia. or built the

18:12.586 --> 18:15.329
cold box, to my specifications. But he was the only 
really old...

18:22.036 --> 18:31.986
I guess he was retired from Mount Wilson, but he was 
still running his machine shop in Pasadena, and I

18:22.036 --> 18:31.986
was referred to him and made arrangements for him 
to build my photometer. But again, I never had any

18:32.427 --> 18:36.571
in-depth conversations with these people. I've 
heard various stories about how the old work was

18:37.512 --> 18:42.357
done, but... Well, let's hear an old story. Well, 
like the first observations of photometry on the

18:43.012 --> 19:12.630
100-inch telescope when they used a ballistic 
galvanometer as the operating across the 10-foot

18:43.012 --> 19:12.630
width of the Newtonian platform on the 100-inch 
telescope to get the first photometric

18:43.012 --> 19:12.630
deflections that were used in some of the early 
galaxy photometry that people like Pettit and

18:43.012 --> 19:12.630
Stevens and Whitford and so on were doing. at 
Lowell when you were there, what did the people on

19:12.830 --> 19:17.375
the staff think of Percival Lowell?

19:20.758 --> 19:30.608
Well, I had the impression that he was a very highly 
respected founder of the observatory. I never

19:30.648 --> 19:31.949
heard anything negative. And the old library 
there, the tours that they held, his founding of

19:33.350 --> 19:41.959
the observatory, his original connection with 
Mars and so on was always very highly regarded, as

19:42.395 --> 19:48.384
far as I could tell. I was never directly, I'd say, 
involved in any of this. I never remember any

19:52.831 --> 19:57.519
conversations relating to Lowell. I had a number 
of conversations with the,

19:57.559 --> 20:09.297
what's

19:57.559 --> 20:09.297
the man who administered the estate? executor, 
not executor, but... Sole trustee or something,

20:12.420 --> 20:14.702
wasn't it? Sole trustee, yes. Was his nephew or 
something like that? Yes, his nephew. Roger

20:19.346 --> 20:30.898
Lowell Putnam was the trustee, and I remember 
going for a hike up Mount Humphreys. We didn't get

20:31.238 --> 20:35.602
to the top, but I remember I went on a hike with him. 
Again, the main theme that came through was...

20:40.462 --> 20:41.263
Lack of money. I never detected anything but 
enthusiasm for doing the best astronomy we can at

20:41.283 --> 20:51.640
this institution, but we don't have much money. 
How did the townsfolk treat the observatory and

20:51.700 --> 20:57.950
the astronomers there? My impression, again, was 
that this was a highly respected institution and

21:05.453 --> 21:15.284
Again, I never detected any animosity or any 
feeling that this

21:05.453 --> 21:15.284
was anything but a real nice thing to have in town. 
And it was a standard viewing place. People would

21:18.147 --> 21:24.774
drive up the drive, and it was always considered 
one of the best places to look over the surrounding

21:18.147 --> 21:24.774
area. Mars Hill was certainly a local 
institution. I just flew over it Saturday, and

21:27.577 --> 21:30.500
there was a hole in the clouds. The only one between 
I think San Antonio and San Francisco, and there

21:32.538 --> 21:39.288
was Flagstaff, and there was Mars Hill with the 
little white domes on top. Of course, Anderson

21:39.308 --> 21:51.385
Mesa development had just started, and there were 
a couple of... Well, there was, I guess... There

21:51.425 --> 21:58.495
was a telescope down there, and I can't remember 
the exact sequence in which these were moved or

21:51.425 --> 21:58.495
built, which was the one connected with the... 
lunar mapping program which was going on there.

22:03.502 --> 22:05.886
And that was being done by, what, the Air Force? 
That was the Air Force. It was an Air Force program

22:07.168 --> 22:23.875
and it was specifically oriented towards

22:07.168 --> 22:23.875
preparing best maps of the moon for the moon 
landings, future moon landings. USGS, I guess it

22:24.462 --> 22:33.410
was, and Gene Shoemaker's program, they were in 
Flagstaff around that time. They were located on

22:33.450 --> 22:36.533
the north side of town, a different location. 
Yeah, I knew Gene Shoemaker, or got to know him

22:37.194 --> 22:50.387
later, because we were both astronaut candidates 
in 1965, but again, I had no direct connection,

22:37.194 --> 22:50.387
just these were interesting programs which were 
going on in the area. There was interest in

22:52.407 --> 22:54.990
specifically the preparation for the moon 
landing. I didn't associate any of this work with

22:55.051 --> 23:01.639
any of the other aspects or any other parts of the 
solar system. It was all very much moon-oriented.

